{
  "doc_id": "42105",
  "text": "The small heat shock protein (hsp)B1 (human hsp27 and its murine orthologue hsp25) is a member of the small hsp family that comprises 10 proteins, including the lens proteins aA-and aBcrystallin, and they all share a conserved C-terminal a-crystallin domain [CITATION_1] . There is now a very extensive literature on the small heat shock protein, mainly describing functions proposed on the basis of experiments performed in vitro, or on cultured cells. HspB1 has been detected in a wide range of human cell types including fibroblasts [CITATION_2] , endothelial cells [CITATION_3] , macrophages [CITATION_4] and neutrophils [CITATION_5] . In contrast, little is known about its function in vivo, and the only murine strain reported to date with impaired hspB1 expression, a knockin mutant expressing a truncated form of hspB1 fused to a b-galactosidase reporter gene, does not appear to display any obvious phenotype [CITATION_6] .",
